**Idea:**

Since both arrays are sorted, we can maintain two pointers, iii and jjj, to traverse arr1arr1arr1 and arr2arr2arr2, respectively. At each step, compare the elements:


If arr1[i]≤arr2[j]arr1[i] \leq arr2[j]arr1[i]≤arr2[j], add arr1[i]arr1[i]arr1[i] to the union (if it is not already present) and advance pointer iii.
Otherwise, add arr2[j]arr2[j]arr2[j] to the union (if it is not already present) and move pointer jjj.
After one pointer reaches the end of its array, append the remaining elements from the other array, ensuring no duplicates are added.
**Time Complexity:**

The two-pointer technique runs in O(n+m)O(n + m)O(n+m) time because each element is processed at most once.

**Code Implementation:**

Below are the implementations in both C++ and Python.

**C++ Code (Approach 1):**

`#include &lt;bits/stdc++.h&gt;
using namespace std;

vector&lt;int&gt; findUnion(int n, int m, vector&lt;int&gt;&amp; arr1, vector&lt;int&gt;&amp; arr2) {
    int i = 0, j = 0;
    vector&lt;int&gt; Union;
    while (i &lt; n &amp;&amp; j &lt; m) {
        if (arr1[i] &lt;= arr2[j]) {
            if (Union.empty() || Union.back() != arr1[i])
                Union.push_back(arr1[i]);
            i++;
        } else {
            if (Union.empty() || Union.back() != arr2[j])
                Union.push_back(arr2[j]);
            j++;
        }
    }
    while (i &lt; n) {
        if (Union.empty() || Union.back() != arr1[i])
            Union.push_back(arr1[i]);
        i++;
    }
    while (j &lt; m) {
        if (Union.empty() || Union.back() != arr2[j])
            Union.push_back(arr2[j]);
        j++;
    }
    return Union;
}

int main() {
    int t;
