Another straightforward method involves using a set to automatically manage duplicate elements.


Insert all elements from both arrays into a set.
In C++, the `set` data structure stores elements in sorted order by default. In Python, after using set union, we simply sort the resulting set to return the union in ascending order.
**Time Complexity:**


**C++:** Insertion operations take O(log⁡n)O(\log n)O(logn) time per element, resulting in O((n+m)log⁡(n+m))O((n+m) \log(n+m))O((n+m)log(n+m)) overall.
**Python:** Set insertion is O(1)O(1)O(1) on average, but sorting the set takes O((n+m)log⁡(n+m))O((n+m)\log(n+m))O((n+m)log(n+m)).
**Code Implementation:**

Below are the code implementations for this approach.

**C++ Code (Approach 2):**

`#include &lt;bits/stdc++.h&gt;
using namespace std;

vector&lt;int&gt; findUnion(int n, int m, vector&lt;int&gt;&amp; arr1, vector&lt;int&gt;&amp; arr2) {
    set&lt;int&gt; s;
    for (int i = 0; i &lt; n; i++) {
        s.insert(arr1[i]);
    }
    for (int j = 0; j &lt; m; j++) {
        s.insert(arr2[j]);
    }
    vector&lt;int&gt; Union(s.begin(), s.end());
    return Union;
}

int main() {
